  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Two homes are listed on the same Brisbane street, on the same week, at similar prices. One is described as a four-bedroom home. The other is described as three bedrooms plus a study. Walked through, the layouts are nearly identical: each has a smaller fourth room, around 2.5 by 3 metres, that could plausibly serve as either a small bedroom or a study. The four-bedroom listing receives twice the inspection volume on its first weekend. The three-bedroom-plus-study listing has half the foot traffic and ends up selling for a meaningfully lower price.</p>

      <p>That outcome is not unusual, and it is not a coincidence. Bedroom count is one of the most powerful filters in real estate search, and the way a home is described in this single field has an outsized impact on the buyer pool, the campaign foot traffic, and ultimately the sale price. Sellers who do not think carefully about bedroom configuration leave money on the table, and sellers who overstate it lose buyer trust. This article walks through how to think about it.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why bedroom count matters disproportionately</h2>

      <p>Buyers on realestate.com.au and Domain filter listings by bedroom count first, before price, suburb, or any other criterion. The filter is at the top of every search. A buyer searching for "4-bedroom homes in Bulimba under $2m" will simply not see your home if it is listed as a 3-bedroom property, regardless of how compelling the rest of the listing is.</p>

      <p>Moving from 3 to 4 bedrooms in the search filter changes the entire buyer pool. Three-bedroom searchers tend to be downsizers, smaller families, or first-home buyers stretching into a larger home. Four-bedroom searchers tend to be growing families, established families, or buyers with home-office requirements. The two pools have different budgets, different motivations, and different buying behaviours. A home that could plausibly belong to either category and is described as belonging to only one is reaching only half the buyers it could.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The legal definition of a bedroom in Queensland</h2>

      <p>There is no strict legal minimum room size for a bedroom in Queensland residential properties. The relevant rules are at the level of the National Construction Code (which sets minimum standards for habitable rooms generally) and local council planning (which can affect how a room is approved when a home is built or extended).</p>

      <p>A room described as a bedroom should typically have a window, ventilation, and reasonable access. Rooms that lack a window or have substandard ceiling height (less than 2.4m for the majority of the floor area) may not be classifiable as a habitable room and therefore should not be marketed as a bedroom. If a room was added to the property as part of an extension, the relevant council approvals should be in place; calling an unapproved structure a bedroom in marketing can create legal exposure for the seller.</p>

      <p>For most homes in Brisbane's inner east, the question is not whether a room is legally a bedroom but whether buyers will accept it as one. The two are different questions, and the second usually matters more.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What buyers expect from a bedroom</h2>

      <p>Buyers have practical expectations of what a bedroom should be, regardless of the legal minimums. A working set of expectations:</p>

      <p>Minimum dimensions of approximately 2.5m by 3m for a single bed with a small wardrobe and bedside table. Smaller than this and the room feels like a study or a home office, not a bedroom.</p>

      <p>Preferably 3m by 3m or larger for a queen bed. The market expects most bedrooms in family homes to fit a queen bed. Rooms that fit only a single bed are bedrooms in a technical sense but read as smaller-than-typical secondary bedrooms.</p>

      <p>A built-in or freestanding wardrobe. A room without a wardrobe is more often described as a study than a bedroom, particularly in inner east Brisbane homes built or renovated since the 1990s. The presence of a wardrobe is one of the clearest visual signals that a room is "really" a bedroom.</p>

      <p>Natural light from a window. A room with no window is rarely accepted as a bedroom by buyers, even if technically habitable.</p>

      <p>A door that closes. Rooms that are open to a corridor or are part of an open-plan area are not bedrooms in the way buyers think about them.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The 'study' question</h2>

      <p>A small room without a built-in wardrobe is typically described as a study or office. Calling a small room a bedroom invites scrutiny: buyers walk through, see the dimensions, see the absence of a wardrobe, and either question the listing or quietly downgrade their internal valuation of the home. The agent loses credibility, and the buyer's emotional engagement with the listing weakens.</p>

      <p>The "3 plus study" description is the honest middle ground. It signals three traditional bedrooms plus a smaller multipurpose room, captures both 3-bedroom and 4-bedroom searchers (because portals typically index "3+study" listings under 4-bedroom searches), and does not mislead. For a home with a smaller fourth room, this is often the strongest description.</p>

      <p>The trick is in the implementation. The listing should clearly call the smaller room a study (in the headline, the description, and the photos), should still appear in 4-bedroom search filters where the portal allows, and should let buyers form their own view of how the smaller room would be used. Some buyers will see a fourth bedroom, others will see a study, and the home appeals to both.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The four-bedroom premium in Brisbane</h2>

      <p>In Brisbane's inner east family markets (Bulimba, Hawthorne, Camp Hill, Carina, Norman Park), four bedrooms commands a meaningful premium over three. Daniel observes a typical premium in the range of 8 to 15% in family-oriented suburbs, depending on the property and the broader market conditions. The reason is straightforward: the four-bedroom buyer pool is deeper, and within that pool, two-parent families with two children, work-from-home parents, and downsizers from larger five-bedroom homes all gravitate to four-bedroom properties.</p>

      <p>The marginal cost of converting a study or rumpus to a proper bedroom (adding a wardrobe, improving the door and window, repainting) is often well worth it before listing. A spend of $2,000 to $4,000 on a wardrobe and minor finishing work can shift the buyer pool meaningfully and add tens of thousands to the result. The agent should walk through the home with this calculation in mind, not just from a styling perspective.</p>

      <p>The conversion is not always feasible. A room without a window cannot become a bedroom. A room that is plainly an office (built-in desk and shelving, no wardrobe space) is hard to repurpose for buyer perception within a few weeks. The right time to think about these conversions is when the seller is planning the campaign, not in the middle of it.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The converse: selling as the wrong configuration</h2>

      <p>Calling a four-bedroom home a "three-bedroom plus study" under-prices the property for the family buyer pool. Some sellers do this conservatively, worried about overstating the home; the result is a campaign that reaches the wrong buyers and produces a softer price. If the home genuinely has four functional bedrooms (each with a wardrobe, a window, and a door that closes, each large enough for at least a single bed), call it a four-bedroom home.</p>

      <p>Calling a three-bedroom home a "four-bedroom" home invites buyer pushback and undermines the agent's credibility. Buyers walk through, see that the fourth "bedroom" is a 1.8m by 2m room with no wardrobe and a sliding door, and immediately question the rest of the listing. The home loses momentum on its first weekend, and the campaign rarely recovers.</p>

      <p>The discipline is to describe the home as it actually is, calibrated to where the configuration sits on the bedroom-or-study line. The right description gets the right buyer pool through the door.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The second-bathroom equivalence</h2>

      <p>Bedroom count is the dominant configuration filter, but bathroom count matters almost as much. Moving from one bathroom to two is similar in price impact to moving from three bedrooms to four. A home with a fourth bedroom but only one bathroom is configurationally unbalanced for the family buyer pool: four bedrooms suggests a family of four or five sharing one bathroom, which most modern Brisbane buyers will not accept. The home sells at a discount to a four-bedroom-two-bathroom comparable.</p>

      <p>For sellers contemplating pre-listing renovations, adding a second bathroom (or upgrading a half-bathroom to a full bathroom) is often the single highest-return improvement available, particularly on homes that already have four bedrooms. The cost is significant ($25,000 to $60,000 typically) but the price impact in inner east Brisbane is usually larger than the spend.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What sellers can do before listing</h2>

      <p>If a study could become a fourth bedroom with simple changes (built-in wardrobe, paint, blinds, a door that closes properly), consider the change before listing. The cost is modest and the buyer-pool shift is meaningful. Talk to the agent about this calculation specifically; a good agent will have a view on whether the conversion is worth the spend for your home.</p>

      <p>If a sleepout, garage conversion, or rumpus is being marketed as a bedroom, ensure it complies with council and that any approvals are in place. Unapproved bedrooms are a real risk: buyers' building inspectors may flag them, finance approvals may be affected, and a contract can fall over at the last minute if the issue surfaces during settlement.</p>

      <p>If the home has a fourth room that is genuinely a study (built-in desk, no wardrobe, smaller dimensions), market it as such and let buyers decide how they would use it. The "3 plus study" description captures both buyer pools and avoids the credibility risks of overstating.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The listing description discipline</h2>

      <p>Describe rooms as they actually function. A study should be called a study. A bedroom should be called a bedroom. Stretching either direction reduces the campaign's effectiveness.</p>

      <p>Include floor plan dimensions for serious buyers. A listing with a clear, dimensioned floor plan removes ambiguity and lets buyers self-select. Buyers comparing multiple listings find dimensioned floor plans far more useful than agent descriptions, and including them signals that the seller is being straightforward about the home.</p>

      <p>Do not stretch. Buyers comparing 30 listings detect inflated descriptions quickly. The campaign that overstates loses trust on the first inspection and rarely recovers. The campaign that describes accurately builds buyer confidence over the course of the campaign.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The inner east Brisbane buyer profile</h2>

      <p>Different buyer pools search for different bedroom counts in Brisbane's inner east, and the right configuration depends on which pool you are targeting.</p>

      <p>Young families typically search for 4 bedrooms. The standard family configuration is a master suite, two children's rooms, and a guest or office room. In suburbs with strong school catchments (Bulimba, Hawthorne, Camp Hill), this is the dominant buyer pool.</p>

      <p>Downsizers from larger family homes typically search for 3 bedrooms. They have moved past the family-with-children stage and are looking for one master, one guest room, and one home office or hobby room. Three-bedroom homes in walkable, established suburbs are highly sought.</p>

      <p>First-home buyers typically search for 2 to 3 bedrooms, often at the smaller end of the inner east price range. They are flexible on configuration and more sensitive to price than to bedroom count.</p>

      <p>Investors typically search by yield rather than configuration, but the bedroom count affects the rental pool: 3-bedroom homes attract families and group rentals, 4-bedroom homes attract slightly larger families or groups.</p>

      <p>Calibrate the listing to your most likely buyer pool. A home with a fourth small room in Bulimba should generally be marketed to family buyers (4 bedrooms or 3+study). A home with three large bedrooms in Hawthorne should generally be marketed to downsizers (3 bedrooms, with floor plan emphasising the room sizes). The agent's read on which pool is dominant for your specific home is one of the most important strategic inputs to the campaign.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The practical framework</h2>

      <p>Bedroom count is one of the most powerful filters in real estate search. Treat it strategically, not as an afterthought when the listing is being drafted.</p>

      <p>Describe rooms accurately. The honest description gets the right buyer pool through the door. The stretched description loses trust on inspection.</p>

      <p>Consider conversions before listing if they expand the buyer pool. A wardrobe and minor finishing work can move a home from "three plus study" to "four bedrooms" for a few thousand dollars, and the price impact is usually well above the spend.</p>

      <p>Talk to the agent about configuration specifically. A good agent has a view on whether your home should be marketed as 3, 3+study, or 4 bedrooms, and that view should be informed by the buyer pool currently active in your suburb. The right configuration call is one of the highest-leverage decisions of the entire campaign.</p>

